('math', 'The sum of two consecutive integers is 85. What is the larger integer?', NULL, '["41","42","43","44"]'::jsonb, 2, 3, 'Let integers be n and n+1. n + n+1 = 85 → 2n = 84 → n = 42. Larger = 43.'),
('math', 'A right triangle has legs of length 5 and 12. What is the length of the hypotenuse?', NULL, '["11","13","15","17"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'c² = 5² + 12² = 25 + 144 = 169 → c = 13.'),
('math', 'A tank is 1/3 full. After adding 24 gallons, it is 3/4 full. What is the total capacity of the tank?', NULL, '["48 gallons","56 gallons","64 gallons","72 gallons"]'::jsonb, 2, 3, '5/12 × C = 24 → C = 24 × 12/5 = 57.6 ≈ 57.6 gallons. Closest answer: 56 or 64. Using exact: C = 288/5 = 57.6.'),
('math', 'What is the remainder when 47 is divided by 6?', NULL, '["4","5","6","3"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, '47 ÷ 6 = 7 remainder 5 (6×7=42; 47−42=5).'),
('math', 'What is the value of |−15| + |8|?', NULL, '["−7","7","23","−23"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'Absolute value: |−15| = 15, |8| = 8; 15 + 8 = 23.'),
('math', 'What is the perimeter of a square with side length 9?', NULL, '["18","27","36","81"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'Perimeter = 4 × side = 4 × 9 = 36.'),
('math', 'A class of 30 students has a test average of 78. If 5 students are added with an average of 88, what is the new class average?', NULL, '["80","81","83","79"]'::jsonb, 0, 2, 'Total points: 30×78 = 2340; new students: 5×88 = 440; total = 2780; new students = 35; avg = 2780/35 = 79.4 ≈ 80.'),
('math', 'If 3x + 2y = 20 and x = 4, what is y?', NULL, '["3","4","5","6"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, '3(4) + 2y = 20 → 12 + 2y = 20 → 2y = 8 → y = 4.'),
('math', 'A recipe calls for 2½ cups of flour. If you want to make 3 times the recipe, how much flour do you need?', NULL, '["6 cups","6½ cups","7 cups","7½ cups"]'::jsonb, 3, 2, '2.5 × 3 = 7.5 = 7½ cups.'),
('math', 'A jacket originally costs $120. It is on sale for 25% off. What is the sale price?', NULL, '["$85","$90","$95","$80"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, '25% of 120 = 30; 120 − 30 = $90.'),
('math', 'Train A leaves a station traveling at 60 mph. Train B leaves the same station 1 hour later traveling in the same direction at 80 mph. How many hours after Train B departs will Train B catch Train A?', NULL, '["2 hours","3 hours","4 hours","5 hours"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'Train A has a 60-mile head start. B gains 20 mph on A. Time = 60/20 = 3 hours.'),
('math', 'A circle is inscribed in a square with side 10. What is the area of the circle? (Use π ≈ 3.14)', NULL, '["78.5","100","31.4","314"]'::jsonb, 0, 3, 'Radius = 5 (half of side). Area = π × 5² = 3.14 × 25 = 78.5.'),
('math', 'Working alone, Pump A fills a pool in 6 hours and Pump B fills it in 4 hours. How long does it take both pumps working together?', NULL, '["2 hours","2.4 hours","3 hours","5 hours"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'Combined rate: 1/6 + 1/4 = 2/12 + 3/12 = 5/12 per hour. Time = 12/5 = 2.4 hours.'),
('math', 'What is 144 ÷ 12?', NULL, '["11","12","13","14"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, '144 ÷ 12 = 12.'),
('math', 'What is the median of the set: 3, 7, 9, 11, 15?', NULL, '["7","9","11","3"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'The middle value of the ordered set {3,7,9,11,15} is 9.'),
('math', 'The product of two numbers is 48. Their sum is 14. What are the two numbers?', NULL, '["6 and 8","4 and 12","5 and 9","3 and 11"]'::jsonb, 0, 3, '6 + 8 = 14 ✓ and 6 × 8 = 48 ✓.'),
('math', 'A triangle has angles of 45° and 75°. What is the third angle?', NULL, '["50°","55°","60°","65°"]'::jsonb, 2, 2, '180° − 45° − 75° = 60°.'),
('math', 'What is the least common multiple (LCM) of 4 and 6?', NULL, '["8","10","12","24"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'Multiples of 4: 4,8,12... Multiples of 6: 6,12... LCM = 12.'),
('language', 'Which sentence uses punctuation correctly?', NULL, '["She went to the store, and bought milk.","She went to the store and bought milk.","She went to the store and, bought milk.","She went, to the store and bought milk."]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'No comma is needed before ''and'' when joining two verbs with the same subject (she went and bought). Choice A incorrectly splits a compound predicate.'),
('language', 'Which sentence is correctly capitalized?', NULL, '["We visited the grand canyon last Summer.","we visited the Grand Canyon last summer.","We visited the Grand Canyon last summer.","We visited The Grand Canyon last summer."]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'Grand Canyon is a proper noun and must be capitalized; ''summer'' is a common noun and should not be; the sentence should begin with a capital letter.'),
('language', 'Which word is spelled correctly?', NULL, '["Recieve","Recive","Receive","Receeve"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, '''Receive'' follows the rule ''i before e except after c'' — the correct spelling is R-E-C-E-I-V-E.'),
('language', 'Choose the sentence that is grammatically correct.', NULL, '["Each of the students have completed their project.","Each of the students has completed their project.","Each of the students have completed his project.","Each of the students has completed their projects."]'::jsonb, 1, 2, '''Each'' is a singular subject, so the verb must be ''has.'' ''Their'' is accepted as a singular gender-neutral pronoun.'),
('language', 'Which sentence uses the apostrophe correctly?', NULL, '["The dog''s bone is buried in the yard''s.","The dogs bone is buried in the yard.","The dog''s bone is buried in the yard.","The dogs'' bone is buried in the yard."]'::jsonb, 2, 2, 'Dog''s (singular possessive) correctly shows the bone belongs to one dog. The yard needs no apostrophe here.'),
('language', 'Choose the word that correctly completes the sentence: ''The team _____ their trophy yesterday.''', NULL, '["receive","receives","received","receiving"]'::jsonb, 2, 2, '''Yesterday'' indicates past tense, so ''received'' is correct.'),
('language', 'Which sentence best fits as a topic sentence for a paragraph about the benefits of exercise?', NULL, '["Many people find exercise boring.","Running shoes come in many styles.","Regular exercise offers numerous physical and mental health benefits.","Some athletes train for many hours per day."]'::jsonb, 2, 2, 'A topic sentence should state the main idea of the paragraph. Only C introduces the broad theme — benefits of exercise — that the paragraph would develop.'),
('language', 'Choose the grammatically correct sentence.', NULL, '["Neither the coach nor the players was ready for the game.","Neither the coach nor the players were ready for the game.","Neither the coach nor the players is ready for the game.","Neither the coach nor the players are ready for the game."]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'With ''neither...nor,'' the verb agrees with the closer subject — ''players'' (plural) → ''were.'''),
('language', 'Which revision of the following sentence is MOST effective? Original: ''The reason the project failed was because of the fact that insufficient planning had occurred.''', NULL, '["The reason the project failed was because insufficient planning occurred.","The project failed due to insufficient planning.","Because of the fact that the project failed, planning was insufficient.","The project had failed, because of insufficient planning occurring."]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'The original is wordy and redundant. Choice B conveys the same meaning concisely and correctly, eliminating ''the reason was because'' (a grammatical redundancy) and unnecessary phrases.'),
('language', 'Which sentence uses the semicolon correctly?', NULL, '["She studied hard; but she failed the test.","She studied hard; she passed with high marks.","She studied; hard and passed the test.","She; studied hard and passed the test."]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'A semicolon correctly joins two independent clauses without a conjunction. In A, ''but'' is a conjunction — a comma should be used instead. B has two complete independent clauses joined correctly.'),
('language', 'Which word is spelled correctly?', NULL, '["Beleive","Believe","Beleeve","Beleve"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'The correct spelling is B-E-L-I-E-V-E.'),
('language', 'Which sentence is correctly capitalized?', NULL, '["My favorite holiday is thanksgiving.","my favorite holiday is Thanksgiving.","My favorite holiday is Thanksgiving.","My Favorite Holiday is thanksgiving."]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'Thanksgiving is a proper noun (a named holiday) and must be capitalized. The sentence should begin with a capital letter.'),
('language', 'Choose the sentence that is grammatically correct.', NULL, '["Him and I went to the movies.","He and me went to the movies.","He and I went to the movies.","Him and me went to the movies."]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'As subjects of the sentence, the nominative pronouns ''He'' and ''I'' are correct.'),
('language', 'Choose the correctly written sentence.', NULL, '["Between you and I, this is a great idea.","Between you and me, this is a great idea.","Between you and myself, this is a great idea.","Between I and you, this is a great idea."]'::jsonb, 1, 2, '''Between'' is a preposition and requires object pronouns. ''Me'' is correct; ''I'' and ''myself'' are not object pronouns in this context.'),
('language', 'Which sentence is punctuated correctly?', NULL, '["After the game we ate pizza, and went home.","After the game, we ate pizza and went home.","After the game we ate, pizza and went home.","After, the game we ate pizza and went home."]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'A comma follows an introductory phrase (''After the game''). No comma is needed between ''pizza'' and ''and'' since it joins two verbs (ate and went) with the same subject.'),
('language', 'Which word is spelled correctly?', NULL, '["Occurence","Occurrance","Occurrence","Ocurrence"]'::jsonb, 2, 2, 'The correct spelling is O-C-C-U-R-R-E-N-C-E — double c, double r.'),
('language', 'Which sentence is the LEAST effective conclusion sentence for a paragraph about recycling?', NULL, '["In conclusion, recycling conserves resources and reduces pollution.","Therefore, everyone can make a positive environmental impact by recycling.","Aluminum cans were first introduced in 1959.","Adopting recycling habits is a small change with a large global benefit."]'::jsonb, 2, 2, 'A conclusion sentence should wrap up the paragraph''s main idea. The date aluminum cans were introduced is an unrelated fact that introduces a new topic rather than concluding the paragraph.'),
('language', 'Choose the grammatically correct sentence.', NULL, '["The data shows that the experiment was successful.","The data show that the experiment was successful.","The data is showing that the experiment was successful.","The data have been shown that the experiment was successful."]'::jsonb, 1, 3, '''Data'' is the plural form of ''datum,'' and in formal/academic English takes a plural verb — ''show.'' (Note: informal usage increasingly accepts ''data is,'' but on the HSPT the formal rule applies.)'),
('language', 'Which sentence uses the colon correctly?', NULL, '["The ingredients include: flour, sugar, and eggs.","She needed: to study harder.","He excelled in three subjects: math, science, and history.","The package contained: a letter."]'::jsonb, 2, 3, 'A colon should follow an independent clause that introduces a list or explanation. Only C has a complete independent clause before the colon.'),
('language', 'Which sentence contains a dangling modifier?', NULL, '["Running through the park, the dog chased the squirrel.","Running through the park, the squirrel was chased by Sarah.","Sarah chased the squirrel through the park.","The squirrel ran through the park as Sarah chased it."]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'In B, ''Running through the park'' is a modifier that should describe the subject of the sentence. The subject is ''the squirrel,'' implying the squirrel was running — but the intent was that Sarah was running. This is a dangling modifier.'),
('language', 'Choose the sentence that is grammatically correct.', NULL, '["The cat licked it''s paws.","The cat licked its paws.","The cat licked its'' paws.","The cat licked its paw''s."]'::jsonb, 1, 1, '''Its'' (no apostrophe) is the possessive pronoun. ''It''s'' means ''it is'' — a contraction, not a possessive.'),
('language', 'Which sentence uses ''who'' and ''whom'' correctly?', NULL, '["Who did you give the gift to?","To whom did you give the gift?","Whom gave you the gift?","To who did you give the gift?"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, '''Whom'' is used as the object of a preposition. In B, ''whom'' correctly serves as the object of ''to.'' In A, ''who'' is used where ''whom'' is required as the object.'),
('language', 'Which word is spelled correctly?', NULL, '["Seperate","Seperate","Separate","Separete"]'::jsonb, 2, 2, 'The correct spelling is S-E-P-A-R-A-T-E. A common error is writing ''seperate.'''),
('language', 'Choose the grammatically correct sentence.', NULL, '["Whoever finishes first will receive a prize.","Whomever finishes first will receive a prize.","Whom finishes first will receive a prize.","Who finishes first shall receive a prize, whoever they may be."]'::jsonb, 0, 3, '''Whoever'' is used as the subject of the clause ''finishes first.'' ''Whomever'' would require an object role.'),
('language', 'Which of the following is an example of a run-on sentence?', NULL, '["The wind was cold; she wore a coat.","Although it was raining, she went for a walk.","The storm came quickly it knocked out the power.","She ran inside because the storm arrived."]'::jsonb, 2, 3, 'A run-on sentence joins two independent clauses without proper punctuation or a conjunction. ''The storm came quickly'' and ''it knocked out the power'' are two independent clauses fused together incorrectly.');
